<fr:p>A <fr:em>Grothendieck topology</fr:em> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[J]]></fr:tex> on a <fr:link
type="local"
href="rs-0001.xml"
addr="rs-0001"
title="Category">category</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[C]]></fr:tex> consists of,
for each object <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  C]]></fr:tex>, a collection of <fr:link
type="local"
href="rs-0061.xml"
addr="rs-0061"
title="Sieve">sieves on
<fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex></fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[J(x)]]></fr:tex>, called <fr:em>covering sieves</fr:em>, so that:
<fr:ul><fr:li><fr:em>identity</fr:em>: the <fr:link
type="local"
href="rs-007D.xml"
addr="rs-007D"
title="Maximal sieve">maximal sieve</fr:link> at <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> covers <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex>;</fr:li>
  <fr:li><fr:em>stability</fr:em>: if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> covers <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[y\xrightarrow {f} x]]></fr:tex> is any map, then the <fr:link
type="local"
href="rs-0078.xml"
addr="rs-0078"
title="Pullback of a sieve">pullback
  sieve</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f^*S]]></fr:tex> covers <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex>;</fr:li>
  <fr:li><fr:em>transitivity</fr:em>: if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> covers <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[T]]></fr:tex> is a sieve on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> so that, for each map
  <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[y\xrightarrow {f} x \in  S]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f^* T]]></fr:tex> covers <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[T]]></fr:tex> covers <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li></fr:ul></fr:p><fr:p>Equivalently, say that a sieve <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> covers a map <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[y\xrightarrow {f} x]]></fr:tex> if the
pullback <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f^*S]]></fr:tex> covers <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex>. Then the axioms state: <fr:ul><fr:li>if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\in  S]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> covers <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>;</fr:li>
  <fr:li>if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> covers <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>, then it covers <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[fg]]></fr:tex> for any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g]]></fr:tex> where the
  composition makes sense;</fr:li>
  <fr:li>if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> covers <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[T]]></fr:tex> covers each <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g\in  S]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[T]]></fr:tex> covers
  <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li></fr:ul></fr:p><fr:p>A category equipped with a Grothendieck topology is called a <fr:em>site</fr:em>.</fr:p>
  
    
    
